with Devin is a little more like just being,  

921
01:12:22,880 --> 01:12:27,440
more as having an interface to hand 
off tasks and build tasks. And so,  

922
01:12:28,640 --> 01:12:37,280
the parallel that I would draw is when we invented 
Python, obviously... It's like, in many ways the  

923
01:12:37,280 --> 01:12:43,040
description and the outlining of tasks, obviously 
it was a different paradigm, but I think certainly  

924
01:12:43,040 --> 01:12:49,040
it was nowhere near what folks typically 
think of as management bureaucracy today. 

925
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:58,320
And I think that with Devin, a lot of it is just 
like, it's more like finding the right levels of  

926
01:12:58,320 --> 01:13:03,920
abstraction that you could work with Devin on, and 
just finding the workflows that work really well,  

927
01:13:03,920 --> 01:13:10,800
and the obvious thing to say here is, it's like 
you can always have Devin take a first pass at  

928
01:13:10,800 --> 01:13:16,720
things. And so you have Devin take the first 
pass, if it's great, you merge it right away,  

929
01:13:16,720 --> 01:13:22,160
if it needs some touch up, you can obviously 
give that feedback, for example, but a lot of  

930
01:13:22,160 --> 01:13:29,520
it is like, it's more about, basically making 
Devin part of your flow than it losing control,  

931
01:13:29,520 --> 01:13:34,080
which I think is the main thing that 
folks are scared of with management.

932
01:13:34,080 --> 01:13:37,840
Are you thinking about a manager Devin? 
Like a Devin that manages other Devins?

933
01:13:37,840 --> 01:13:43,440
Yeah, yeah. So, for what it's worth, Devin 
can start other Devins through the API,  

934
01:13:43,440 --> 01:13:48,560
right? And so, we've seen this happen quite 
a bit of times, where naturally if you have  

935
01:13:48,560 --> 01:13:53,120
some big tasks that you want to do, Devin will 
do this all the time, it'll chunk up and then  

936
01:13:53,120 --> 01:13:55,920
[inaudible 01:13:53] into smaller Devins. And 
so, it's the kind of thing that you need to give  

937
01:13:55,920 --> 01:14:00,240
Devin the credentials to be able to do that, it's 
not currently something that is default enabled,  

938
01:14:00,800 --> 01:14:03,600
but I can certainly imagine as time goes 
on that there's more and more of that

939
01:14:03,600 --> 01:14:04,960
Devins all the way down.

940
01:14:04,960 --> 01:14:09,440
Yeah, yeah. I think the thing that's kind 
interesting too is, with humans, the way I almost  

941
01:14:09,440 --> 01:14:18,080
say it, in technical terms, it's like there's 
this coupling of a context and a thread, and what  

942
01:14:18,080 --> 01:14:25,280
I mean by that is basically, each human can only 
operate a single threaded on the work that they  

943
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:28,480
do, and they have their set of context, and then 
there's other humans obviously who can do other  

944
01:14:28,480 --> 01:14:33,600
stuff at the same time, but they have their own 
context. With agents, one of the cool things is  

945
01:14:33,600 --> 01:14:38,320
you can have an agent that's doing multiple lines 
of exploration at once, but is sharing all of the  

946
01:14:38,320 --> 01:14:45,040
context of everything that they find, and so I 
think that this is very early, and I think we'll  

947
01:14:45,040 --> 01:14:50,800
see this, but folks obviously love to talk about 
basically systems of agents communicating with  

948
01:14:50,800 --> 01:14:55,600
one another, and I think that there will be a lot 
of new paradigms to build for, once we get there.

949
01:14:55,600 --> 01:15:01,200
And it's so interesting what you said about the 
decision between having one Devin and only one  

950
01:15:01,200 --> 01:15:05,680
Devin do all the things, and you just tell them 
things and they fire off jobs versus you have  

951
01:15:05,680 --> 01:15:09,920
five Devins, and they're each doing individual 
things, it's such an interesting decision to make.

952
01:15:09,920 --> 01:15:12,320
Yeah, yeah, yeah, for sure.

953
01:15:12,320 --> 01:15:15,920
Okay, two more questions. Maybe the 
most counterintuitive thing you've  

954
01:15:15,920 --> 01:15:21,360
learned so far building Devin, that maybe goes 
against startup wisdom, common startup wisdom?

955
01:15:21,360 --> 01:15:26,800
Something I've thought about a lot lately as 
we've built this is, this is not my first company,  

956
01:15:26,800 --> 01:15:32,720
actually for a lot of us, it's not our first 
company, I think of our 26 or 27 people total  

957
01:15:32,720 --> 01:15:38,480
on the team, I think 18 of us have started our own 
company before this. And yeah, one of the things  

958
01:15:38,480 --> 01:15:45,840
I think about is, there's actually your point 
about cliches I think really spoke to me as well,  

959
01:15:45,840 --> 01:15:50,080
which is, there's the really common things 
which you hear all the time in startups,  

960
01:15:50,080 --> 01:15:54,400
where you're like, you got to move fast, or you 
got to hire great people, it's like, okay, well,  

961
01:15:54,400 --> 01:16:01,200
obviously you do, I wasn't planning on not hiring 
great people, I wasn't planning on going slow. And  

962
01:16:01,200 --> 01:16:05,760
similarly it's like, yeah, you really got to build 
something that people want. And there's these  

963
01:16:05,760 --> 01:16:11,440
three to five things which are always repeated, 
and they're always the common wisdom in startups. 

964
01:16:11,440 --> 01:16:15,520
And I definitely had this idea as a 
founder, when I was starting initially,  

965
01:16:15,520 --> 01:16:20,080
that, all right, so those are the three to five 
basic things, but as you get really deep into it,  

966
01:16:20,080 --> 01:16:24,480
you spend a lot of years into it, you learn 
all of the thousands of other things that  

967
01:16:24,480 --> 01:16:31,200
you have to learn to build a company. And I 
think to some extent that's, of course, true,  

968
01:16:31,200 --> 01:16:36,320
and there's lots of little details that you'll get 
into with all these different things, including  

969
01:16:36,320 --> 01:16:41,840
team building, and product, and strategy, and 
engineering decision-making, and fundraising,  

970
01:16:42,720 --> 01:16:48,880
and sales, and every other component. But I also 
realized that as time has gone on, more and more,  

971
01:16:48,880 --> 01:16:54,480
I felt like building companies well sometimes just 
comes down to doing those three to five things  

972
01:16:54,480 --> 01:17:01,680
just even more than you could possibly expect.
And so, with us, it's like... And everyone says we  

973
01:17:01,680 --> 01:17:05,440
go fast, but it's like, yeah, we had a hackathon 
in November, we had another hackathon in December,  

974
01:17:05,440 --> 01:17:10,880
we started the company officially in January, 
we got the prototypes out to initial users in  

975
01:17:10,880 --> 01:17:14,960
February, we did a launch in March, we got our 
first customers in April... It's just like,  

976
01:17:14,960 --> 01:17:20,320
basically truly pushing the pace in every 
spot where we possibly could has really made a  

977
01:17:20,320 --> 01:17:24,480
difference for us. And similarly, it's like, yeah, 
everyone always says you should hire great people,  

978
01:17:24,480 --> 01:17:34,240
but I think that the truth within that truth is 
basically you should fight to all ends basically,  

979
01:17:35,040 --> 01:17:41,440
to get the folks that you really want to bring 
in. And one of my favorite stories to share is  

980
01:17:42,240 --> 01:17:46,720
we had a candidate who came and interviewed, he 
was a junior at MIT, so he was very, very young,  

981
01:17:46,720 --> 01:17:51,920
and we gave him an interview, and he did way 
better than almost any of the full-time candidates  

982
01:17:51,920 --> 01:17:55,360
that we had ever talked to. And so, we said, hey, 
what do you think about taking some time off of  

983
01:17:55,360 --> 01:17:59,040
school and working with us and building out Devin?
We really think you're just going to be able to  

984
01:17:59,040 --> 01:18:02,640
come in and just have a ton of impact already 
from day one. And he thought about it for a  

985
01:18:02,640 --> 01:18:08,240
while, and he came back and he said, you know 
what? I'm down, I want to do it, but my parents  

986
01:18:08,240 --> 01:18:13,280
really want me to graduate from school, and I'm 
just not sure there's a way to make it work. And  

987
01:18:13,280 --> 01:18:23,600
so, we talked him more and just understood the 
situation, and then we flew to North Carolina,  

988
01:18:23,600 --> 01:18:27,280
went straight from the airport to his parents' 
house, had dinner with him and his parents,  

989
01:18:27,280 --> 01:18:34,320
we talked a lot, a really nice Gujarati family, we 
gave them some gifts and just talked to them about  

990
01:18:34,320 --> 01:18:39,600
it, and try to understand what would it take, and 
what would we need to make work. And they just  

991
01:18:39,600 --> 01:18:43,760
said, it sounds like a great opportunity, but 
we really want our son to be able to graduate. 

992
01:18:45,120 --> 01:18:50,800
And we talked that through and we figured out 
a setup basically, where he could work for us  

993
01:18:50,800 --> 01:18:56,240
essentially full time, but then come in for his 
required classes, and do what he needed to do to  

994
01:18:56,240 --> 01:19:01,360
get the diploma basically, but no more than that. 
And we talked that through, and then we got to a  

995
01:19:01,360 --> 01:19:07,040
point where everyone was happy with that, and then 
went straight back to the airport and flew right  

996
01:19:07,040 --> 01:19:11,840
back, basically. And that was the first and only 
time that I've ever been in North Carolina, and it  

997
01:19:11,840 --> 01:19:16,800
was just a great trip. And it is the kind of thing 
where it's like, hiring great people is one thing,  

998
01:19:16,800 --> 01:19:23,760
but truly just never giving up, and really giving 
it everything that you can to make it work for  

999
01:19:23,760 --> 01:19:28,080
people who really makes sense to be on the team. 
And he's been with us on the team for over a year  

1000
01:19:28,080 --> 01:19:31,600
now, and he's been an incredible, incredible 
engineer, and we wouldn't be here without him. 

1001
01:19:31,600 --> 01:19:35,280
And similarly, we had someone else who was 
again, really, really talented candidate,  

1002
01:19:35,280 --> 01:19:40,080
did amazingly well, very young, and had a lot 
of great offers at a lot of other companies,  

1003
01:19:40,080 --> 01:19:44,800
and we were talking to them about, he wanted 
to start his own company someday as well,  

1004
01:19:44,800 --> 01:19:50,240
and we were talking to him about certainly a lot 
of the obvious things, which are having him meet  

1005
01:19:50,240 --> 01:19:55,520
our investors, or get to do work with customers, 
or see a lot of these other components so that  

1006
01:19:55,520 --> 01:19:59,840
when the time came that he would have all the 
experience he needed to start his own company.  

1007
01:19:59,840 --> 01:20:06,240
But one of the other things that was big is he 
was talking with a lot of great companies already,  

1008
01:20:06,240 --> 01:20:09,680
he didn't want to burn any bridges, 
and so we actually worked with him and  

1009
01:20:09,680 --> 01:20:14,080
basically hand wrote all of his rejection 
responses to each of the other companies,  

1010
01:20:14,080 --> 01:20:19,360
and worked with him on it to say, here's how 
you should say it in a way that's going to  

1011
01:20:19,360 --> 01:20:25,040
come off as that you really did appreciate the 
time with them, and that obviously you want to  

1012
01:20:25,040 --> 01:20:29,680
remain close with them and stay in touch. And it 
was the kind of thing obviously where it's like,  

1013
01:20:29,680 --> 01:20:35,200
look, obviously our job is to make sure that he's 
happy enough that he doesn't want to leave at any  

1014
01:20:35,200 --> 01:20:39,280
time in the near future, but I think it's 
the kind of thing where the way that you  

1015
01:20:39,280 --> 01:20:45,760
put together a really, really great team is 
by fighting for what's right for them too.

1016
01:20:45,760 --> 01:20:50,880
Wow, those are incredible stories. And it 
makes so real these, as you say, cliches,  

1017
01:20:50,880 --> 01:20:56,080
hire the best people, this is what it sounds like 
to hire the best people. This is what it takes.

1018
01:20:56,080 --> 01:21:01,520
Yeah, no, and I was just saying, a 
lot of things we've fought very hard  

1019
01:21:01,520 --> 01:21:06,800
to just reimagine things from the ground up 
because a lot of it really is just thinking  

1020
01:21:06,800 --> 01:21:12,000
about where do we think the technology 
is going over the next five, 10 years,  

1021
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:15,440
and what is the place that we 
want to have in that future?

1022
01:21:15,440 --> 01:21:18,480
I wonder if people are going to be 
fighting for the best Devin someday.  

1023
01:21:18,480 --> 01:21:22,597
They're just going to [inaudible 01:21:19] Devins.

1024
01:21:22,597 --> 01:21:22,602
Yeah.

1025
01:21:22,602 --> 01:21:22,640
They're [inaudible 01:21:22] so smart.

1026
01:21:22,640 --> 01:21:26,720
I'll give you overtime pay, 
benefits, free healthcare,  

1027
01:21:26,720 --> 01:21:28,600
and everything, and then the Devin's like...

1028
01:21:28,600 --> 01:21:31,440
Three Devins like Magic: The Gathering cards.

1029
01:21:31,440 --> 01:21:31,760
Yeah.

1030
01:21:31,760 --> 01:21:35,760
And then just going back to your three to five 
things. So, essentially this is incredible advice,  

1031
01:21:35,760 --> 01:21:41,040
essentially, it's like you always hear hire the 
best people, move fast, build things people want.

1032
01:21:41,040 --> 01:21:46,960
Yeah, build something people want, stay as 
close as possible to your customers, and then  

1033
01:21:46,960 --> 01:21:51,280
I think the other thing is just always think about 
where things are going, not where they are today.  

1034
01:21:51,280 --> 01:21:58,240
I feel like those are the five things, which is... 
Especially in AI, with things moving so fast,  

1035
01:21:58,240 --> 01:22:02,480
and there's so much great talent, I feel like a 
lot of these are even more true, where it's like  

1036
01:22:03,440 --> 01:22:06,320
it's not just thinking about where things are 
going to be in 10 years, it's like thinking  

1037
01:22:06,320 --> 01:22:11,040
about what's going to happen next week. And 
obviously, things are moving very quickly,  

1038
01:22:11,040 --> 01:22:17,440
and it is very hard to predict, but you really 
have to be very rigorous with yourself, I'd say,  

1039
01:22:17,440 --> 01:22:25,040
about thinking through those things and evaluating 
all of the decisions that you make in that lens.

1040
01:22:25,040 --> 01:22:28,960
And staying focused is the big takeaway 
to me here, is it ends up feeling like  

1041
01:22:28,960 --> 01:22:31,680
there's 1000 things you should do, 
but it's always these five things.

1042
01:22:31,680 --> 01:22:33,200
Yeah.

1043
01:22:33,200 --> 01:22:38,480
Scott, we covered a lot of ground. We went through 
every question I had, which is great, is there  

1044
01:22:38,480 --> 01:22:42,240
anything else that you want to share? Anything 
else you want to leave your listeners with, maybe  

